Hi,How's it going? my name is Jodie Peterson, Director of Investment Opportunities at Micromentor Inc, I have been assigned to inform our esteem users of a new cash-flow development for US based entrepreneurs only. We thought you would be interested in Paxful Inc regarding purchasing and instantly selling American giftcards to major European e-trade firms.Paxful converts giftcards to cash via sales to European e-traders  bidders in exchange for a low commission, for example you can purchase a $100 giftcard then submit to paxful for instant conversion and you get a double cash back of $208 (Paxful retains $8 commission) so you instantly earn $100 profit. Please note that you will be subject to a maximum of $2,500 per day to be earned. Minimum age requirement is 18. If interested kindly send an email to paxfuleu@europe.comThank you for choosing Micromentor,Customer Care www.micromentor.org

Hey David,Yes, I believe I can help. As I mentioned, I think it would be tough to provide you with a full-blown plan but we can definitely bump a few ideas off of each other. Can you tell me the direction you want to take the website? Also, just so I get a feel of what your business is all about, can you provide me your goals, budgets, partners, etc...? Hello Nina,Thank you for providing me with more information about your business. So the first thing that I would like to mention is that it looks like you have launched a nice website which provides users with a simple user-experience. I think that you are in an industry that can be considered quite competitive- the reason being is that art is something that is bought with 'disposable' income. Meaning, it is a want, not a need. Don't take that the wrong way, but I think that you should get into the mind-set that you are trying to sell something to people that could go somewhere else and by something from a competitor (another artist). What do you do? You go beyond the user-experience of just having a website and selling your pieces and make them into something that people 'need.' How do you do that?Well, this can be tricky because it is all in how you sell your pieces. Of course, you should take the traditional routes, i.e. etsy, pinterest, your website. But you should also see how other artists got their name out and consider what they did and how you can do it, as well. For example, running private events- you do something that creates exclusivity to your brand because they may be one-of-a-kind pieces. Building out a quick landing page about people's favorite piece and the story behind it. Basically, take it beyond just an art work and turn it into something that people strive to hear more about.I think that this would be the first piece in really differentiating yourself and creating a name for yourself.Thanks!Dan

So in short, I think that you best plan is just to keep building. I think that you have an idea that can work and that you have to stick with it and keep building. I would say that you are approximately 30-50% at your minimum viable product, but you have to show users that your website is better and more beneficial than your competitors. What is your traffic like right now? How many are acquired through social, search engine, etc?I think you are taking the right direction, but I would say put some time and effort into SEO and inbound marketing + adding more to your website to create a more three dimensional user experience.Thanks,Dan

Yes, there is a difference between getting someone to like your product, verses getting someone to want/need your product.I think that events can work well if you do them properly and on a low-budget. I wrote an article for an art event I ran, check it out: https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20141127195743-62169886-how-to-throw-a-large-event-for-under-50I would recommend setting up a Pinterest 'shop' and an etsy store. Grow your exposure as much as possible and use all forms of mediums that can potentially help 1) expose you and 2) help you sell more product.Thanks,Dan

Hey Karen,How are you? Thank you for contacting me in regards to your business and asking for the help. In all honesty, understanding when to ask for help is definitely a big leap for an entrepreneur. I checked out your website and it actually looks pretty good. I think, of course, there are UI (user-interface) changes that can be made to improve the experience, but I totally understand that you are coming from a boot-strapped background for this.I do want to help out on this project, but unfortunately I am currently spread pretty thin working between 60-80+ hours/week. If you have specific questions, I can help there. My biggest recommendation (and what I did) is learn by doing. By that, I mean go on Google,Youtube, etc... and read as much as you can in your free time. Watch videos about UI/Ux, read articles, read about SEO, SEM, social media marketing, etc.. and just get a very strong grasp on it. Next, test. So create a google analytics account (or hire someone on indeed or fiverr to do it for $5). See what works and what doesn't. Build a mailing list and grow organically.Hope this little bit helped and I wish you the best for your magazine. If you need anything, please feel free to reach out.Best,Dan
